title: For Trade:  federal 38spcl 125 grain nyclad hp
postcontent:
The Nyclad bullet used in the .38 Special standard velocity cartridge is from a very soft lead and has a yawning hollow point; it is very easy for the  slug to expand in tissue. The bullet’s nylon coating reportedly helps reduce airborne lead, and it helps prevent the soft lead from building up in the revolver barrels. 
As every shooter knows (or should know), there are no magic bullets. Expect none of the commercially available .38 Special cartridges to provide instant incapacitation of drug-crazed dragons. The Evan Marshall statistics show that from a 2’’ barrel the standard velocity 125 grain Nyclad .38 hollowpoint has a one-shot-stop about 63% of the time. The .38 Special 158-grain roundnose has a one-shot-stop record of only around 49% when fired from a 2’’ barrel. The +P 158-grain lead semi-wadcutter hollowpoint is successful from a 2’’ barrel 67% of the time -- ---------------------------------REDACTED----------------------
will trade for some .357 ammo

title: For Sale/Trade:  1800's Belgian Parlor Pistol
postcontent:
For sale/trade is a Belgian Parlor Pistol from the 1800's. It has been looked at by a proffesional and he has confirmed that it is most likely Belgian. There are no markings except 2 notches carved on the under side of the barrel. The very tip of the hammer was broken off a long time ago. Send me an offer! Willing to ship.

Parlor pistols and rifles (zimmerschutzen from German, "room marksman" or "room shoot") were popularized in the mid to late 19th Century, particularly in the Germanic countries, as a way to entertain guests, have family fun, and to increase one's shooting skills. Generally heavy barreled and often elaborately engraved rifles (zimmerbusche) were produced for clearly upscale clients. These generally used a Flobert (CB-Cap) cartridge chambered a few inches from the muzzle. Sometimes equally elaborate parlor pistols (zimmerpistole) were chambered for Flobert cartridges or simply used a percussion cap. In this country, a small, almost toylike parlor pistol was briefly manufactured by Remington in 1860.

title: For Trade:  Remington M91 Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
This is a Remington M91 Mosin Nagant manufactured in 1918. These later Remingtons are a bit more hard to find than 1917 dated examples. This particular rifle has not spent any time in Finland, as is typical for many M91's, but I've never been 100% sure on it's history. It has some Spanish Civil War features, but a few of the parts are not correct for a rifle which spent time in Spain, so I've never considered it as such. It's possible the incorrect parts were added by someone here in the States, but there's no saying for sure. The other possibility is it's from a Balkan nation (Romania, Albania, ect).

In any case it's not import marked and has a pretty nice bore on it. A bit dark, but strong lands and grooves.

I'd prefer to trade for another C&R rifle first, but I might sell it if I get a good offer.

Feel free to ask any questions or for more pictures.

title: For Sale:  Galil sporter, 7 mags
postcontent: *WILL TRADE FOR NICE GLOCK 26 & GOOD 12 GUAGE PUMP IF YOU WANT AN AWESOME DEAL!* .223/5.56 Galil this rifle has AR accuracy while having AK reliability and improved ergonomics. Galil's have the highest combination of accuracy and durability of all assault rifles. Its a Caspian milled receiver marked century arms with an F stamp, if you know what that means. Basically the parts are all IMI issue mil-spec (which is now IWI), imported by century. The receivers marked century were either built by ORF or Caspian. The ORF models did not all get properly heat treated so the Caspian starting with serial number GLN (what I have) is very desirable. Furthermore there was a recall on several early models so they started marking the bottom of the new models with an "X" for passing condition and an "F" for the finest condition firearms. The F stamped lower receivers are obviously the most desirable and mine is also an "F" stamp. Galils like mine are almost never seen up for sale, and if you buy a cheap CAI Galil the receiver will not be properly heat treated, and the head spacing will be off at the very least. Thats why my Galil is directly comparible to a $2000+ IMI al original Galil because that's basically what it is... When Caspian made the receivers they parkerized the whole thing including the chamber... I have since polished the chamber just because thats how God and Uzial Gal (the inventor of the Galil and Uzi) intended it to be. The headspacing is correct as well as the height of the feed ramp. I have added quad rail, front grip, and polished chamber. Comes with 7 mags and possibly up to 200 rounds ammo. Shoots steel case all day. Shoals area. Trade for glock 26, stock Saiga rifles/shotguns + cash or possibly multiple weapon/accessory trades.
